dismissalText.commentary: Hashim Amla run out (Shah) 34 (31b 8x4 0x6 40m) SR: 109.67

dismissalComment.html: Shah gets Amla run out with a direct hit. Gibbs had charged down the track and mistimed a shot past the bowler and set off with the stroke. The ball went behind the stumps and Shah came across from mid-on. Amla was very late in responding and tried to run down the track between the stumps and the throw but the ball beat him to crash into the stumps at the striker's end. Against the run of play, a wicket has fallen. Amla was caught ball watching there. Gibbs looks very surprised and stares long and hard at Amla. Very good effort from Shah, he picked it with his left hand, swung around as he passed the ball to the right and fired down the stumps

headshotImage.caption: Jacques Kallis player page headshot cutout, 2021
headshotImage.longCaption: Jacques Kallis player page headshot cutout, 2021

dismissalComment.html: massive wicket, and an even bigger controversy looming here. Kallis swishes loosely outside off to a ball that nips off the seam, and appears to beat the bat. Prior claims a comfortable edge and appeals, and Simon Taufel - after a consultation with his colleague - refers the decision upstairs. The third umpire, Ian Gould, can only adjudicate on whether the ball carried, not whether there was an edge or not. And so, Kallis has to go. And he is livid ...   But the snickometer shows there was an edge.

commentTextItems.html: That's the game. Flintoff brings up the victory with a swing to the deep backward square leg boundary. He dashed outside off, got outside the line and lapped it around the corner. England lead the series 4-0. Pietersen is all smiles in the pavilion. A glum Kallis walks out with his players. Huge cheers for Flintoff and Shah.

commentPostTextItems.html: Flintoff has been named the Man of the Match. Can England sweep the series 5-0? Or will SA get a consolatory win? Join us on Wednesday. For now, good bye and good luck.

commentTextItems.html: another short-pitched delivery, Flintoff moves outside leg, has a waft but can't connect.
Flintoff charges out and Nel fires in a bouncer and Flintoff falls on his backside to get away from that.
slower one, coming in, turned to midwicket for a single

commentPostTextItems.html: The big dark pregnant cloud is still going through labour pains. Don/'t you push down now! gloom descends on the arena.

commentTextItems.html: thrusts his back foot across, opens his stance and clubs a full pitched delivery over extra cover for couple of runs

commentTextItems.html: Oh another full toss and Flintoff kills it to deep midwicket boundary.  Just 7 more.
The full tosses keep coming. Flintoff works his bottom-hand over time to swing it to cow corner.

commentPreTextItems.html: AGain the crowd boo at poor Kallis, who makes a field change

commentTextItems.html: low full toss outside off stump, swinging away, driven to long-off
Shah eases his captain's nerves with a off drive to wide long-off for couple of runs

commentPreTextItems.html: Ian Sutherland: "That Hempstead shower has moved east and is is now drenching Saffron Walden."

commentTextItems.html: waist-high full toss on the off and middle, Shah can only push it back to the bowler. Pietersen is chewing his nails in the pavilion.
down the track and on drives to deep midwicket for a single

commentTextItems.html: comes down the track, Botha shortens the length , Shah pushes it towards the off side of the pitch and Botha dives to stop.
Shah gets the crowd going again with a well-timed and more importantly, well-placed sweep shot to deep square leg
drives down the ground for a single to Andre Nel at long-on

commentPreTextItems.html: Botha stops just about the release time. And the crowd boo as he turns back!

commentTextItems.html: Now the crowd erupt in joy as their Freddy charges out to loft over long-on. The white ball is flying everywhere on this dark gloomy evening.
Shah jumps out, takes it on the full and drives to long-off
What a shot! Flintoff walked down the track and flayed a length delivery through extra cover. It sped away to the boundary. The crowd roar

dismissalText.commentary: Hashim Amla run out (Shah) 34 (31b 8x4 0x6 40m) SR: 109.67

dismissalComment.html: Shah gets Amla run out with a direct hit. Gibbs had charged down the track and mistimed a shot past the bowler and set off with the stroke. The ball went behind the stumps and Shah came across from mid-on. Amla was very late in responding and tried to run down the track between the stumps and the throw but the ball beat him to crash into the stumps at the striker's end. Against the run of play, a wicket has fallen. Amla was caught ball watching there. Gibbs looks very surprised and stares long and hard at Amla. Very good effort from Shah, he picked it with his left hand, swung around as he passed the ball to the right and fired down the stumps

stories.title: Whitewash looms as England target second spot
stories.subTitle: England v South Africa, 5th ODI, Cardiff
stories.summary: Are England really the second-best one-day team in the world? It's a preposterous notion, and yet, by the time Kevin Pietersen's men go to bed in the early hours of Thursday morning, it could well be an officially-recognised fact

stories.title: Shah backed for a successful run
stories.subTitle: South Africa in England 2008
stories.summary: The only one of Kevin Pietersen's plans that hadn't quite come off, at least until Sunday at Lord's, was Owais Shah's promotion to No.3

stories.title: South Africa overpowered in 20-over thrash
stories.subTitle: England v South Africa, 4th ODI, Lord's
stories.summary: England were once again able to exploit the soft underbelly of South Africa's batting, thanks to a three-wicket haul from Andrew Flintoff and a lacklustre display from an inexperienced lower-order

stories.title: Keeping an eye on the ball, not the money
stories.subTitle: England v South Africa, 4th ODI, Lord's
stories.summary: And so the juggernaut rolls on. Not even the rain, increasing gloom or a return to form for Hershelle Gibbs could stop England's one-day bandwagon, while an early-morning back spasm was no hindrance to Andrew Flintoff
